{
  "title": "Constructive Discontent",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8b79afe674439f2b",
      "text": "I'm a constructive discontent. My friends have accused me of wearing the 'black hat' too often. I often have a healthy feeling of dissatisfaction with how things are, that things could be better, and I have the a desire to do something about the situation. I now understand that this feeling is the precursor to important creative breakthroughs, and tell my story to share some recent and life changing learnings."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6c264555e249ed5b",
      "text": " As I reflect on my career, a pattern does emerge. One of me being dissatisfied, frustrated, even angry, about some aspect of what I saw as an imposed but misplaced education agenda, or some practices in the school I was leading that weren't about learning. This dissatisfaction has motivated me to do act, and to seek solutions and new approaches. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "af5a7b795c60f0cb",
      "text": "The frustration and anger felt was not driven by hate, but rather a compelling belief things should, and could, 'be better' - a [[Virtuous Anger]]. In hindsight what I achieved may not have been overly bold or disruptive innovations, but at the core was to have my school do more for the students, to have learning come alive. I concede what while what I was doing was 'tinkering' with schooling, I know the impacts of these innovations were important for least some of my students - those a standard deviation or more from the mean. The students disengaged from boredom and those disengaged by frustration. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "846cfd9bab03c73b",
      "text": "While people around me seemed happy with how things were, most of the staff and many of my contemporaries included, I could see an opportunity to challenge accepted practice. This was often sparked by [[Colliding Ideas]] collected from various sources, perhaps a conference, a connection between research and an opportunity presented by a particular school context, and the joy of the [[Eureka moment]] when I saw something for the first time. In recent years this disposition has also brought me to more carefully consider my 'why'."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3503d028de767f54",
      "text": "It would be fair to say that early in my career I lacked the courage to challenge the status quo too much. I would certainly not be described as a maverick. And I didn't promote the work for any career benefit. However, that drive to create, change and improve, has always been motivational for me."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "35f701ac4d011004",
      "text": "The feeling of discontent remains, and I am now feeling I need to make a more meaningful difference, not just tinker at the school level. I have an impatience with the dogged persistence of a schooling system tenaciously holding on to old ways and its all encompassing conviction this is the right thing to do. I believe we need a new narrative for schooling, if not a new narrative for humanity. And I realise that what I've been learning recently, although it has challenged me and how I view the world, is offering a meaningful way forward. This is my story."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "712b85df2b7343f7",
      "text": "Next: [[Being Sorted]]"
